The claim that Paul didn't make any money from the scam because he didn't sell his Zoo tokens - is the wool that Paul tries to pull over your eyes: the Zoo tokens and NFTs were created by Paul and sold to investors, where Paul pockets the profits (0.1ETH cost per token to investors, against a minting cost that is pretty negligible). All that money - around $100M worth of ETH (at the time, more now) was supposed to pay for development, but how much was actually paid out to the developers - who claim they were underpaid - and how much was pocketed by different individuals associated with the project? Hopefully we can find in discovery.

Something I imagine will be unearthed in discovery is the history and current state of the game (if it exists) and whether it advanced at all after Logan promised to finish it. The question "what has Logan done to fulfill that promise?" could be important, since if the answer is "nothing" it's going to be pretty hard to argue Coffee's statements were false. It would also settle the question of whether calling it "Logan's scam" is reasonable, as even if it wasn't exclusively his before, it became his after he promised to finish the project. IF he made no effort to follow through on that promise, I'm not sure what else you would call it but a scam.

I AM sure Logan wishes they were both in the UK or Australia. Defamation laws there are brutally rigged in favour of wealthy plaintiffs. As it stands, I think he's going to get slapped with the Streisand Effect while pursuing this case. Reporting on the minutiae of YouTube celebrity drama, beef and misdeeds is a genre that whole channels are based on. The genre's narrative requires a "villain" to be "exposed", and it's almost never the little guy. Those channels will revisit every scandal Logan has ever been even adjacent to, and probably dig up some new ones as well. Maybe he's deliberately trying to build his reputation for villainy as part of his wrestling career.

The issue is that the definition of scam is not representative of the project when we are specifically talking about Logan.
Scam involves as a requirement having a gain of some sort. It can not be a scam if you didn't end up having any gain from said project. And we all know (even Coffeezilla acknowledged) that Logan himself has not sold any of his zoo tokens and as such has not made any income from the project. At all. Like literally 0. In fact, he most likely lost money for this project.
So despite both sentences: "Logan is the creator and frontman of the Cryptozoo project" AND "Cryptozoo is a scam" are factually correct and indisputable. It still is not correct to say that Logan scammed people with Cryptozoo. Because that implies it was Logan to actually scam people, which is also factually wrong when we previously established the two concepts above.

Lu Cai, or Shangdong Cuisine, has a lot of history behind it, and is considered one of the most venerated cuisine families in China. It's well known for using simple ingredients such as salt and green scallions to create a unique deep umami taste, such as in Green Scallions Fried With Sea Cucumbers or Beef Tendon (you probably tasted it in your baozi already). They are also famous for anything made with wheat flour, such as noodles, steamed or baked bread, dumplings, baozi, pan-fried/baked stuffed flatbread (shao bing). Try their potatoes too. And large chunks of stewed meat of any kind. I think you two are gonna be quite at home in Shandong.

Some tips I wanted to share after watching this video.

1. Jagung means 'Corn' or 'Maize' in Malay.

2. Kambing means 'Goat' in Malay, but if used as Sup Kambing, then Kambing means 'Mutton', so 'Sup Kambing' means 'Mutton Soup'.

3. Try out Teh Halia at hawker stalls that sell Teh Tarik. 'Teh' means 'Tea', 'Halia' means 'Ginger' and 'Tarik' means 'Pull', so 'Teh Halia' is 'Ginger Tea' while 'Teh Tarik' means 'Pulled Tea'.

4. You can also try out other neighbourhoods with hawker centres like Changi Village (pronounced as 'Chahng Yee Village'), Tampines (pronounced as 'Tam Per Niece'), Bedok (pronounced as 'Ber Dok'), Marine Parade, Kovan (pronounced as 'Koh Vern'), Old Airport Road, Tiong Bahru (pronounced as 'Tee Ong Bar Roo'), Chinatown and Maxwell.

5. If you like Cassava (known locally in Singapore as 'Tapioca'), then I suggest you patronise this stall at Maxwell Food Centre called Heng Heng Ondeh-Ondeh and Tapioca Cake. Their Ondeh-Ondeh (pronounced as 'On Day-On Day', consists of a palm sugar filled round tapioca ball that is boiled to melt the sugar filling into liquid and coated with grated coconut) and Tapioca Cake (consists of Steamed Tapioca Cake made from Water, Grated Tapioca, Coconut Cream and Sugar, then coated with grated coconut) are their bestsellers.
